After a life or death experience, 8 stitches in my face, all types of reef cuts and 2 years of at least a thousand wipe outs, I can say: I CAUGHT the WAVE I’ve been dreaming with since I started 🥹 It was ALL worth it. 
 
I moved to Bali exactly 6 months ago and one of my MAIN reasons was: To improve my surf!

Indonesia has some of the best waves of the entire world 🤌🏻

What I didn’t know is that I was gonna go through a near death experience, which was very traumatic. 

The first week after, I was very sick and couldn’t even get out of bed because my body was exhausted, my heart was hurting (YES, it was hurting like if I was having a heart attack) and I was constantly shaking and with a crazy fever. I honestly thought I was slowly dying. 

At that moment, my shaman told me to stop surfing for a while and we started a very profound journey of inner work and ceremonies in order to heal. 

One day, I finally felt the call to go back into the water . My passion for surf and my love for the ocean are just so big that I decided to listen and to face my trauma and fears. 

And that was probably the best decision of my life. Here I am surfing some of the best waves of my life 3 months after the event. 

My story continues and I’ll come back with more videos of my progress during the upcoming months and years. 

Thanks for reading 🙏🏼✨ If you got here: Have you had any traumatic experience similar to this one?

Why do I train barefoot? 

There’s some feet freaks out there and I may or may not be one of them 🤑🦶🏻

I get asked all the time why I train barefoot and it’s something I’m very passionate about as many of you know. In short, our feet are our contact with the earth…

We spend most of our days in shoes.. even from the time we are little! 

Unfortunately, this inhibits our sensory feedback, even beyond a performance standpoint, neuromuscular input to the brain. 

And your big toe mobility is a direct Key Performance Indicator of strength up the rest of the kinetic chain, through the knee and especially into the hip. We have to keep them mobile and shoes act as casts. 

So here’s three main reasons to train barefoot:

1) It strengthens all the small muscles in the foot which helps with balance and grip during big lifts. It will also keep you pain free. 

2) Improves toe mobility which is a direct reflection of knee and hip health.

3) Increases proprioceptive awareness. This is your body’s ability to sense its positioning in space. 

Think of movements like a reverse lunge while training, guiding yourself back with control without having to actually watch what you’re doing. 

But also think of reactive scenarios, like stepping off a curb on accident or slipping out of the shower…

Our feet are the first responders, wearing shoes acts as a buffer between the stimulus and the brain. Take care of them! 

I get that walking around a gym barefoot isn’t always an option, and some people think it’s gross 🤷🏻‍♀️ you can wear socks or a great shoe brand is @vivobarefoot

Polishing my L Sit Skills! 

If I wanna lift 20kg (44lb) Kettlebells… I think it’s extremely important to also learn how to deal and work with my own bodyweight. That’s why I’ve been getting into Calisthenics lately. 

One thing is to work with an external load, BUT let me tell you: ANOTHER one is to work with your own. It’s so much more challenging and requires a lot more connection. 

And I’m not just talking about muscle mind connection, I’m talking about the ability to listen to yourself, to feel and connect with your body in ways you’ve never ever connected before. 

This practice is just incredible and I’m here for the long ride. It took me 12 years to get where I am with my regular training. So, I guess it’ll take me something like that to achieve all those “forms” and things I want.

Here we go… it’s gonna be fun and also frustrating (like it already is some days) but it’ll be worth it. To me, at the end of the day, it’s not even about the end goal, but about the person I’ve become throughout the journey.

Let’s get it ✨

I got triggered by a situation yesterday and it hit me so bad that it broke me down into tears, anger, sadness and confusion. 

It showed me something I thought I healed already… (seems I haven’t 🫠)

THIS is health too. Being able to accept our humanity and sit with our feelings without ANY judgement. 

Getting “busy” in order to be distracted is NOT healing. Let the time “pass by” isn’t either. 

This is what I always do when I’m not feeling well and it always works. So, I’m here to share. 

Sometimes is movement, sometimes stillness (meditation/breathwork), sometimes is dancing or singing and sometimes is journaling… TODAY: I had to go through ALL of them because the pain was very intense. 

It was a beautiful “ceremony” (how I love to call it) and it definitely helped me to move and release all those emotions.

Emotions are energy in motion and I love to move them and transform them into love and gratitude for the teaching they bring me. 

That gives me clarity and peace. I know answers would come in the next days. Still feeling low, but it’s totally ok. Embracing my humanity and evolving every single day. 

My self-love increases every time I do this. 

If you’re going through something similar, ask yourself: Why is this person or situation triggering me? 

And what is it that I haven’t healed or need to work on?

80% of our daily movements happen on one leg: Getting out of the car, going up/down stairs, etc. 

So why not train it more for REAL-life saving, functional strength? 

🩺 Imagine this: A quick 10-second balance check during your routine check-ups by doctors. Wouldn’t be awesome? 

After all, it's called a PHYSICAL exam for a reason! 

Let's invest a few seconds to assess our physical function - it's safe, simple, and incredibly effective. This little test can even predict potential risks for various causes of death. 💀

📊 Here's the eye-opener: Those who didn't pass the 10-second single leg balance test often carried higher body weights, faced cardiovascular issues, grappled with high cholesterol, type-2 diabetes, and more common preventable causes of mortality.

💡 So, how can we use this data to not only prevent death but supercharge our function, strength, and resilience? 

It's not just about balance! In many cases, a lack of "balance" stems from low levels of power and strength. And guess what? These two physical traits are often the least trained among at-risk populations. Time for a change, right?

Ready to improve your mobility without spending hours stretching? Elevate your game with FULL RANGE OF MOTION Strength Training 🔥

Here are some of the key benefits: 

* 	Enhanced Muscle Activation: Full ROM exercises engage a broader range of muscle fibers, promoting better muscle development and strength gains.
* 	Improved Flexibility: Regularly working through full ranges of motion can lead to increased joint flexibility, making daily movements easier and reducing the risk of injury.
* 	Injury Prevention: Full ROM training helps improve joint stability and overall biomechanics, reducing the likelihood of strains, sprains, and overuse injuries.
* 	Functional Strength: It enhances your ability to perform real-life activities, making you more capable in daily tasks and athletic pursuits.
* 	Increased Muscle Mass: Achieving a complete range of motion during strength training stimulates muscle growth across the entire muscle group.
* 	Joint Health: By promoting healthy joint movement, full ROM training can help reduce the risk of degenerative joint conditions like osteoarthritis.
* 	Greater Mind-Muscle Connection: Performing exercises through a full range of motion requires greater focus and concentration, enhancing your mind-muscle connection.
* 	Long-Term Mobility: Regularly practicing full ROM exercises can lead to better mobility and flexibility as you age, promoting overall longevity and quality of life.

Knees or hips in pain after running? 

That’s because you’re not training for it. YES… You need to train TO RUN! Like with any other sport and I’m not talking about athletes… 

Whether you are competing or not. Injuries come when you start playing a sport you’re not prepared for. 

Practice makes progress, but let me share a secret: 

The true magic happens when you pair your practice with sports specific training.

Some benefits here: 

Sport-specific injury prevention

Each sport has the potential for different injuries, for example, a soccer player is at higher risk of a hamstring injury. This is because the quadricep muscle is naturally stronger – due to the player mostly kicking forward.

Each sport has its own thing!

Sports-specific power training

Most athletes will benefit from an increase in power. A 100m sprinter needs power to lengthen stride. Plyometric training performed in the gym can help an athlete enhance power and increase sprint performance.

Sports specific conditioning

Conditioning the body for their sport and the time of play. For example, rowers and cyclists will have a greater focus on aerobic capacity whereas an AFL player or soccer player will have a higher focus on endurance.

Sports don’t enhance athletic inefficiencies. In fact, they expose them!

For every "effect," there's always an underlying "cause."

Posture isn't fixed; it shifts with the activity and how long you do it, whether it's sitting, running, or lifting. 

What you observe is the body's way of adapting and organizing itself to best tackle the immediate task at hand.

Desiring improved posture?

Equip yourself better for the task.

Focus on the "causes," not just the "effects."

It's an alternate viewpoint to consider an individual's state of readiness.

Not all exercise statements are created equal—let’s decode the difference:

🏋️‍♂️ “No bad exercises” doesn’t mean “all exercises are right.” Context matters.

Here’s how I approach exercise selection:

* 	Safety first: Exercises aren’t risky; readiness is. Proper programming aligns exercises with your capabilities. Danger lurks where you’re unprepared.

* 	Goals steer us: Each exercise targets specific traits—flexibility, strength, power—shaping your journey.

* 	Adaptation matters: It’s about tailoring exercises to your abilities, not one-size-fits-all. From front squats to back squats, options abound for unique outcomes.

A bit more than a year ago I signed up for the RKC and it was just my second time touching a bell ever 🤣🤦🏼‍♀️ I didn’t read what the test was or what the certification was about 😅 I just wanted to learn and thought it was gonna be a chill workshop. 

What is the RKC? The Russian Kettlebell Challenge. In my opinion, one of the hardest certifications ever🥵 Why? Because to pass, you need to do 100 snatches in 5 minutes with a specific weight (not light at ALL). Plus other tests… 

A chill weekend??? JA JA JA 🤣 Definitely not. It turns out I was a whole chaos. Was not strong enough to do the weight I was supposed to and my technique was soooo BAD. I mean: 2nd time EVER touching a bell 🤣

I still showed up every day and did what I could. Finished the weekend and took some months to learn with @jlanghans_fit and the @reload.pt team 🤩 which is THE BEST in the game. 

Passed the test and promised myself I was gonna stay consistent and keep practicing till that 16kg (35lb) bell felt like a feather. 

The thing is… then I moved to Uluwatu (Bali) where there are ZEROOO hardstyle bells (the ones I learned with). So I had to get used to the huge bells you see, which make everything 100 times harder, specially if you have small wrists (like me🙄).

Still committed and set the goal to be able to do a full complex with the 16kg by the end of the year with great form. Yesterday… I  ACHIEVED IT! Yay 🤩

What a journey and what a life! Loving my bells and my practice. Thanks @coach_darius for motivating me and be patient 🙏🏼
